          "body": "The chapter's commissioning verse — *therefore write the things which you have seen, and the things which are, and the things which will take place after these things* — has been read in two main ways by orthodox interpreters. The dispensational reading takes it as the literary outline of the book itself: 'things you have seen' = chapter 1 (the inaugural vision), 'things which are' = chapters 2-3 (the seven letters to current churches), 'things which will take place after these things' = chapters 4-22 (eschatological future). The amillennial/idealist reading takes the threefold expression as a comprehensive phrase ('write all of it — past, present, and future') rather than a strict outline. Both readings are orthodox; both honor the text. What is not in dispute is the verse's grounding: the *therefore* (*oun*) anchors the commission in the identity of the One who has just been revealed. John writes — and the church reads — under the authority of the One who holds the keys."
